{{Class 3|hexagon=2|class=2|entity=Entity Infestation; Non-Entity Hazards|color-h=210|color-l=15%|color-s=38%|security=Managed Stability}}
==Description==
{{Blurimage|file=archi.png|width=345px|caption=The surface.}}
'''Level 335''' resembles a massive, ever-expanding abyssal ocean, constantly covered in humid fog. Scattered throughout the ocean are fractured archipelagos, containing dilapidated buildings and houses, roads, other types of human infrastructure, and some limited degree of flora. Most of these archipelagos have the majority of their landmass submerged underwater, with the visible land and infrastructure being only the 'tip of the iceberg'. The visible amount of ground is quite sparse, with individual landmass clusters only approximately 5-15 kilometers across. The level has a day-night cycle, with each lasting approximately 8 hours.
{{Blurimage|file=LONE.png|width=345px|caption=Lonely, foggy expanse.}}
Even though observable land seems limited, underground tunnel systems span into complex, sprawling, albeit claustrophobic, layers. The tunnels are reinforced with concrete composite and have a cylindrical geometric design to withstand external water pressure. These layers seem to be divided into multiple complexes for specific purposes, such as rest, maintenance, communications, and daily routine. Some levels are flooded with dirty, still water, either fully or partially. Contact with this water without recommended equipment can lead to painful rashes or temporary sickness.
{{Blurimage|file=DOWNWEGO.png|width=345px|caption=Into the tunnels.}}
Occasionally, deep-water interferences from undocumented anomalies can cause archipelagos to fracture into multiple, smaller subcontinents and sink deeper into the water. These interferences can also cause tsunamis, strong waves, or inexplicable weather changes. These events are impossible to predict and can happen at any time. It is also seemingly impossible to avoid these events from happening. Civilization within Level 335 is forced to mitigate casualties during these occurrences instead of eliminating them. Despite archipelagos fracturing into multiple pieces, the tunnels still connect anomalously. This makes the tunnel system crucial for transportation to different archipelagos. However, this doesn't mean the tunnels themselves are immune to damage, as constant maintenance and reconstruction are still required after underwater ripples cause structural failures.

The deeper one traverses into the tunnels, the more environmental instability and danger become present. Entities, especially hostile ones, will start to appear more frequently, especially in darker or rustier regions. Furthermore, the lack of human presence dramatically increases one's likelihood of getting lost or dying. Food, water, and other necessities will also become increasingly difficult to find. The legal exploration of these deeper regions usually requires a lengthy process of paperwork, background checks, and official government training.

Various abandoned and rusty ships may appear, floating on the sea. These vessels are often seen capsized, but some are seen still standing upright. The interior of these ships is what one would expect—accommodation, entertainment, deck, and redundancies. The types of ships vary widely, ranging from modern cruise liners to old-fashioned RMS ocean liners to military-grade warships. These ships are essential resources to the ADF Navy.

==Entities==
Entities are rarely encountered on the surface and in the upper tunnel systems, but an abundance can be found residing deeper into the tunnels, as mentioned above. Various species of marine life can also be seen, usually swimming in the Sunlight and Twilight zones. Level 335 is noted to have one of the most diverse marine biospheres. Some common entities are [[Entity 3|Smilers]], [[Entity 62|Aranea Membri]], and [[Entity 46|Narco Jellyfish]], along with other level-specific entities. Many of these entities breathe a unique gas designated "Chemical-335".

===Chemical-335===
{{Blurimage|caption=Tunnel section with highly concentrated volumes of Ch-335, hence the jagged walls.|file=Screenshot 2026-05-21 205955.png|width=290px}}
Chemical-335 is a highly dense elemental gas whose origin is within Level 335, hence the name. Ch-335 has a pale beige color that is only visible in high concentrations. Otherwise, when dispersed in the atmosphere, Ch-335 is mostly invisible to the naked eye. Ch-335 is predominantly present in the mid-Twilight or Midnight Zone and deeper areas of the ocean, or in deeper regions of Level 335's tunnel system. Most living specimens in these harsh-environment areas tend to rely on Ch-335 for respiration rather than oxygen.

For baseline humans, Chemical-335 is highly dangerous. Constant exposure to Ch-335 results in the rapid displacement of oxygen in the bloodstream due to its higher affinity for human hemoglobin than oxygen. Within 45-60 seconds of unmasked exposure, individuals may begin to experience severe vertigo, followed by limbic system disorientation, causing subjects to experience unpredictable emotional impulses while fully conscious and unable to restrain themselves. Afterwards, one may rapidly lose consciousness and undergo cellular hypoxia, leading to death. Conversely, species that rely on Ch-335 for respiratory functions, when introduced to high amounts of oxygen, cause violent cellular oxidation and, subsequently, instant death. This biological limitation makes researching these obscure creatures significantly more difficult.

Besides the biological toll, Chemical-335 also creates a unique structural hazard threat. By reacting with water molecules and ambient water moisture, it creates a highly dense, acidic vapor that gradually yet aggressively attacks solid structural materials such as steel or concrete. This vapor makes these materials highly prone to micro-fracturing, which could severely damage structural support beams and cause entire sections to collapse under their own weight. While the vapor itself isn't immediately dangerous to humans, provided one is wearing clothing, prolonged exposure can lead to severe health effects such as chemical burns and heart problems.

==Colonies and Outposts==
<br>
[[File:ANCHORIA2.png|center|frameless|400px|link=]]
<br>
The State of Anchoria is a relatively old nation-state residing within Level 335. Anchoria is renowned for having one of the highest populations for a nation that controls territories exclusively at a single level, with more than 12,382 citizens. Most of its population is concentrated on Bernhart Island, the largest island in Level 335 and Anchoria's capital. Around 85% of the middle and lower-class population resides within Anchorian-controlled tunnels. The remaining 15% upper-class and elite population receives the privilege of living on the surface, but occasionally evacuates down into the tunnels during a catastrophic geological event. The official language is Anchorian English, a variation of English with notable grammar changes and specific vocabulary. Anchoria's main currency is designated 'Stern'. The culture and religion of Anchoria are rich and complex, yet remarkably homogenous and conservative.

Despite Anchoria's geographical isolation and cultural radicality, it still regularly receives international aid from other groups, mainly through the expansive tunnel system. This aid involves the shipment of logistics such as necessities, technology, money, and information, ensuring the State remains functional. Anchoria leans heavily towards socialist authoritarianism, but citizens are still granted a decent amount of civil rights and economic freedom. Money and property are generally evenly distributed within the population, with the rich earning only about 3.6 times as much as the average person. The fishing industry significantly contributes to Anchoria's economic output, with groups willing to pay for exotic traditional seafood. Anchoria also seems to maintain a monopoly on the fishing industry, as other groups are prohibited from fishing in Level 335 without an official permit.

Anchoria's military force is sizeable but not as advanced as other groups'. Its military consists of around 229 active men and 679 in reserve. The Navy and Coast Guard of the Anchorian Defense Forces (ADF) are the most heavily invested in by the Department of Defense. Besides playing a major role in protecting Anchoria's seas and maintaining the monopoly on fishing, they also frequently survey the area to intercept threats and warn of threats to important locations in advance.

==Entrances and Exits==

===Entrances===

*Multiple stationary entrances (such as Sector 4, Sector 29, Sector 13, etc.) allows for interlevel communication and trade between Anchoria and other groups of interest or nations.
*Can be entered through any outdoor water-themed level, such as [[Level 7]], [[Level 657]], and [[Level 290]].
*[[The Hub]].

===Exits===

*Multiple stationary exits (such as Sector 4, Sector 29, Sector 13, etc.) allows for interlevel communication and trade between Anchoria and other groups of interest or nations.
*Going through certain doors that are slightly less dilapidated could lead to [[Level 1]] or [[The Hub]].
*Going deeper into the tunnels increases your chances of randomly noclipping, usually to an aquatic level or an industrial level.

