<div style="font-family: Plush-Trial; font-size: 35px; text-align: center">Whistler's Manifesto</div>
<big><big><center><span style="font-family: Plush-Trial">Introduction</span></center></big></big>
<div style="font-family: Plush-Trial>
The event was not grand; it wasn't a spectacular or brilliant scene of destruction. If you were there, you'd see their bodies freeze in place, eyes unblinking as the ground itself shuddered, the surface gradually cracking under the weight of its own tectonic movement. That gave them plenty of time to move and save themselves, but not enough time to stop it from happening. There existed only the inevitability, the creeping dread as the cracks began to spread inland and the clouds began to change color. Maritime forces, despite their best efforts, couldn't reach all of the islands by the time it was already too late for the people there. But the worst part wasn't the event itself; it was what happened right after. A population in the thousands crammed into a single island, waiting silently. Families praying for a familiar figure that will never come again, people losing the places that made them who they were. Even the rich were sleeping on the same moldy mattress as the rest of us.

The official reports on the Anchorian Geological Crisis were released five years ago. The document was full of dates, geography, and numbers. But statistics, admittedly, can be a misleading truth. They are a summary of the story, not the plot. I felt disappointed, hell, a bit offended by it, how it disregards the full picture. And as the last representative, or at least human representative, of Anchoria, I feel like it is my duty, my responsibility, to serve the State one last time. I have compiled a collection of old diary entries, images, research, and personal memories to share this personal story about being an operative in the New Frontier Initiative. These retellings may not accurately be what happened, but it was what I could salvage and restore. Hopefully, it will also give you an idea of how many other people like me lived during these times.

I also intend to write this one last piece for more personal reasons, to preserve my and Anchoria's legacy and history, and for these stories to thrive even when the precursors eventually die or become discarded in the ocean of human history. This will probably be the first and last time you ever hear from me again. This is to be my final message to humanity, since this is the last thing I'll write ever again, which is why I posted this on the Internet for free. To whoever you are out there, enjoy the read and the rest of your day.


<big><big><center><span style="font-family: Plush-Trial">Descent</span></center></big></big>

The air got thicker every second the rusty metal box descended. I could smell it even through my suit, which was a hybrid of a CBRN and an atmospheric diving suit. I was almost thrown off my own seat as the elevator shook violently. The lights flickered irregularly, as if they were blinking in Morse code. I genuinely couldn't care less about any message it was trying to send, whether it was a cry for help or a cheerful story. Not like I could, even if I wanted to, since I was on the verge of throwing up any second now. I blankly stared at the elevator's metal walls, trying to imagine something on them. Nothing showed up. Each minute on that thing was like an hour or two.

"Alright, Reg 6... tunnelward, now," said Trench. "Make sure your equipment is still functioning."

"Aye," we muttered in unison, yet I didn't bother to look at him, still staring at the wall. I silently reached for my zippers, slowly moving my hand towards the top until I felt that small piece of metal. Alright, check. And then I covered my respiratory filters. No airflow, which was a good sign, but suffocating. The nausea was more present than ever. I let out a gag. My vision spun, but I managed to snap back into consciousness. I let out a sigh, of relief or of exhaustion, whatever it was. Coast was making sure the pressure valves of The Freezer were still intact since it kept jamming every other time we ran tests. And Rough was loudly knocking on the drones, which thankfully made them work this time. Saved us a lot of trouble, for sure.

I reached for my holster and pulled out what they call the "Equalizer" and gave it a quick checkout as well. It was honestly a pathetic excuse for a sidearm. It was designed to paralyze, not actually pierce the skull or anything. They would've never given us real bullets, not after what happened to the last remaining "survivor" of Regiment 42. His body, at least what was left of it, was the only one retrieved in time. The doctors said his skull was pierced wide open with remnants of lead in it.

Besides that, everything seemed to be functional, for now at least.

A ding rang through the elevator as the metal doors screeched open. It opened up to what the elevator was, just stretched on forever. I got my ass up and trudged out the door, small puddles of dirty water soaking up my boots. Rough was pulling The Freezer and the storage crate out of the elevator, its wheels slightly creaking and making a painfully high-pitched noise as it slid on the scratchy floor. Before we could even orient ourselves, a sharp, double-tone chime cut through the static in our headsets.

"Regiment 6, this is command. Confirm safe arrival at North Sector-33," said a raspy female voice.

"Command, this is field commander Trench. Confirming safe arrival at North Sector-33," replied Trench.

"Acknowledged, Regiment 6. Remember the objective. Your team should collect Wild Obscura plant samples and Walking Jellyfish flesh samples and safely store them in the Preservation & Containment Crate to send back. The next designated safe zone, "Superbia", should be 2.4 kilometers from your current position. But be advised, Sector-33 has been unmonitored since the structural containment sealing of May 2028. You are operating outside of active ADF defense perimeters, so ensure HQ is aware of environmental data every 25 minutes. Godspeed, 6. Over."

The ceiling had a thin crack as droplets of water escaped from those minuscule crevices. They drop steadily, one at a time, each one adding more to the puddle. It felt weirdly peaceful, the slow, structured dripping, or maybe I'm really stressed out. Rough rummaged through his heavy tactical backpack and took out a damaged-looking drone, barely the size of my head. His finger pressed on the activation button, and its blades whirred to life. I look at the tunnel ahead of us and then down at my dusty, cracked tablet. The screen illuminated in the darkness like a dying matchstick.
