NOTE: DATA BOUND TO CHANGE
</div></div></div>
<br>
"Jimmy just sent back a signal!" exclaimed Coast.

His finger pressed on the tablet screen. The drone's propellers echoed louder with each corridor it passed. I was still looking at that leakage from earlier. No sooner had I turned around than it was already a few feet close to my face, slowly making its way down into the ground. I hate to admit it, but it caused me to jump back a bit. Rough bent down, picked that thing up, and placed it squarely back into his bag.

"Field agent Whistler reporting back to command, North Sector-33 Chem-335 levels are at 0.028%, AQI is 128, PM levels are at 2.3, Ozone levels are at 68 ppb. Current threat criticality yellow." I said.

"Copy that, Whistler, maintain current vector. Over."

"According to the calculations, it should be fairly airly for... another 2000 meters, more or less," said Coast. "We're clear to advance."

Trench didn't hesitate further. In a swift action, he clicked his tactical light onto his rifle's under-barrel. A stark, blinding white beam illuminated the dilapidated hallway ahead of us, scaring some bugs away as they retreated into the shadows. We marched onwards in silence, rhythmically breaking it with our footsteps and the skittering of whatever lay within the walls. It grew uncomfortably warmer with each step, and the suit was definitely not great help. It was difficult trying to fit through certain corridors in this bulky sleeping bag they call a suit. A pro tip in these scenarios was always to inhale and exhale slowly, but doing that with recycled, filtered air that smelled suspiciously putrid was as difficult as you'd expect.

"Oh come on, it's not the ocean's retribution, islandmates. They're only gonna send us down here to retrieve what, a few pieces of tissue? And inspect for structural damages?" Rough chuckled. "R'member our deal? Whoever dies first pays for everyone's tuna sandwiches."

"What if everyone dies, huh?" I joked.

The compass I was holding kept twitching sporadically because of the erratic magnetic fields, so it was completely useless. We had to rely on the drone's internal compass and the map roughly built from past Regiment's accounts, which was bad if we wanted to keep this thing's battery alive and the taxpayers happy, and the map wasn't entirely accurate, meaning we still had to take turns and find the correct pathways ourselves. We followed it for a while until it led us to a gateway, with a sign overhead spelling out three words in a gold font: "TOWN OF SUPERBIA". 

The air didn't exactly improve, but at least there was more space to breathe. Rough finally let go of The Freezer and our storage crate and sat on the floor, breathing heavily. I remember reading about Superbia somewhere in a newspaper section. They claimed that this was a niche, exotic vacation spot in the Northwestern part of the tunnels, famous for withstanding impossible conditions, being the farthest down civilization has ever gone here, and for its weird food harvested from even weirder lifeforms. But all I saw were pitiful underground slums where pickpocketing cases were as common as walking. Maybe living here was living authentically in nature? It's been abandoned ever since the Crisis of '28 hit, so I guess I'll never get to experience it myself. Well, it's just good to sit down for a bit, take a break, and eat lunch, maybe even go for a walk later in the fresh air, no?

"Command, reaching Sector-33 checkpoint 'Superbia', some 2400 meters from the starting point. We'll be here for a while for our lunch breaks," said Trench

"Regiment 6, I expect that y'all will remember to do the environmental readings and structural integrity check now that you've reached a temporary haven in proximity to the objective, yes?"

"Duly noted, command, over."

Everyone was rightfully exhausted. Sitting on an empty park bench, I scoured my bag and pulled out a can of rations. In it were 5 pieces of stale crackers and ground-up shrimp paste with a bit of fish flakes as garnish. It was disgusting any other day, and I'd drink like half a bottle of water after to wash away the stinky breath, but I guess food tastes better when you're starving. That's how training for me went in my rookie days. Occasionally, I kept my stomach empty for breakfast, only ate a few protein crackers, and then trained till noon, which would obviously make me a lot hungrier than everyone else initially, but I was the only one there who wouldn't gulp everything down as quickly as I could and throw up later. Obviously, I knew this was bad for me, even back then, I'd do anything to endure another day, and it would be hard to quit since I did this out of habit. Frankly, I don't think I would survive as an officially recognized military man with this habit, especially since this was only somewhat resembling the actual military training I had to undergo for exploration and research in hazardous environments.

The other guys were just silently minding their own business. Rough was sitting on the opposite bench from me, next to an Obscura plant, specifically a domestic one, those plants you'd see sold in markets within the upper layers as room decoration and a sign of luck because they extraordinarily tolerate the dark and lack of Oxygen very well. Just like how Rough was completely unfazed by the environment, leaning back and chewing his food like he'd tasted worse. Only a few meters away were Trench and Coast huddled over The Freezer, faces illuminated by that dim, artificial blue light emitting from their screens, with Coast still chewing on his half-finished meal. Coast was meticulously checking for any fractures or damage that could've gone under the radar during our 2400-meter descent. He was also making sure that the wiring on the drone was clean of dust. Trench, on the other hand, just stood there observing and occasionally giving advice or trying small talk with Coast, to which Coast replied with a series of subtle grunts. To be fair, Coast was one you'd call introverted. Oftentimes, he's doing his own thing... things that math and engineering guys do... and ignoring conversations, even when we called for his attention directly, unless it was for something important, of course. That doesn't mean we don't appreciate him; we'd be lost with broken boulders if it weren't for his expertise. 

I wasn't sure what to do then, so I just said something to break the silence.

"Not gonna lie, it's pretty stupid. You know, the fact that they brought us down here to collect some meat from jellyfish that aren't even scientifically classified as jellyfish and some plants that aren't scientifically classified as plants." I brought up. "Like, I was thinking they'd make us map out the place or maybe even reclaim territory. Honestly, only reason they sent me down here is for the biology shit!"

"Reg 42 n' 27 already did that a few months ago. That's why we didn't get completely lost when our compasses became junk. And hey, trust the process." Rough smirked. "They... always send us down here... for a reason."

"God... god, what's wrong with this stupid machine?" snapped Coast unexpectedly.

We looked over to him with concern. "What?" Trench questioned. "Did you do something wrong?"

"The descent data told us we're 2400 ems down. But we shouldn't have? I- nothing makes sense! It just doesn't!"

The answer only made us more confused.

"Everything's fucking wrong! The angle is wrong, the pressure readings don't match, and the structural scans don't match; it shouldn't make any sense that we're even standing here breathing. Either something's messing with my mind, or the telemetry is garbage, and the code is trash. I want two words with whoever programmed this garbage fire."

"Hey man, it's no surprise. The Wake's full of weird shit, and I just fuck with it" said Rough dismissively

"Oh my, go fuck yourself Rough-"

"Could it be that the tunnels suddenly shifted? I mean, we've seen it pull that shit when the Crisis happened, so it's possible." I said.

"Tunnels don't shift several hundred meters without everything collapsing, Whistler! If it did shift, then everything would've failed, like, the pressure would've changed, and something would get broken!" replied Rough angrily

"Okay, pay attention!" Trench called. "This anomaly will not hinder us from the mission. The best we can do right now is report it to command for informational and data-logging purposes and continue with what we're doing."

This shut Coast down, but he still seemed disgruntled and gave dirty stares to everyone on the team. I think he mumbled something about Trench being a "formal loser" as well.

The barely working streetlamps flickered irregularly, just like those lights back in the elevator, and those were our only light source besides our flashlights. It was like we were blinking faster than our eyes actually blinked. I fought through the darkness and entered an abandoned restaurant with my flashlight in hand. The place had a broken windowpane and a missing back door, which were already signs that something had happened. My suspicions were confirmed the moment I glimpsed a red symbol spray-painted onto the walls and almost tripped on a few bullet casings. Was it paint or blood? I check the counter. There was a single cash register with its drawer jammed, a telephone, and a few copies of the Anchorian Times. Something to pass the time, perhaps? I picked a random newspaper, sat down on one of the chairs, and started reading. The title looked quite familiar...

<div style="background-color: white; margin-left: 10px; margin-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 5px; margin-right: 5px; padding:5px 10px; color: black; font-family: Georgia">

<big><big><center>DOUBLE-HOMICIDE OF LAW ENFORCEMENT AGENTS IN SUPERBIA & ALLEGED EXTREMIST SEPARATIST FACTION CONNECTIONS</center></big></big>
{{Underline|000000}}
'''May 15th, 2028''' — that date was when two police officers, Coral Hartman and James Miller, stopped responding to dispatchers and other patrol units. While police departments initially thought this unnatural silence was police radio errors caused by minimal environmental reality-bending, which was somewhat common in Superbia, after investigations by local law enforcement agencies close to the area, their bodies were found mangled, partially dismembered, in two separate blood-soaked puddles. Both police helmets sustained massive dents on their upper parts, and their gear was also found non-functional, suggesting the use of heavy blunt-force instruments before the ritual. The perpetrators left behind mysterious text, symbols, and drawings depicting a radical humanoid creature resembling fish-folk in Anchorian culture, posed in an almost evangelic, divine form.

“Ve authoritee willn't saive us from the ocean’s retribution, so appeased will thou be with unheard loyalty from we, and our bodies elevated into the godly form of Man” scrawled under the creature’s symbolic depiction.

[[File:SYMBOL2.png|284px|frameless|center|link=]]
<br>
Two days before the murders, the production of local Ghuffish and other Superbian seafood delicacies had abruptly halted in Superbia, with only 2000-3000 kilograms being transported to the surface per day instead of the usual 7000. This massive, inexplicable 60% cut caught the attention of the Anchorian Ministry of Economics & Logistics and, eventually, even the Anchorian military. A special task force unit was sent down to investigate this mysterious phenomenon. While it seemed as if nothing too abnormal was happening in Superbia, after a few days of investigation, armed operatives were met with a horrid sight. After exploring a recently decommissioned government building, 3 decomposing corpses, potentially more, were found, impaled with sharp weaponry, and suffocated in high concentrations of Ch-335 gas. These injuries and deaths were allegedly self-inflicted. This discovery was made on the same day of the murders, which led to the assumption that these incidents were interconnected. However, the mission itself was cut short after a panicked firefight happened between an unidentified group of individuals and the team, resulting in one member sustaining heavy injuries and being hospitalized in Saint Ancorra's Hospital.

Furthermore, three days earlier, on May 12th, false rumors were spreading not just on Superbia but on other towns of a grand apocalyptic disaster, after a crazed and panicked Superbian man, now in government-mandated therapy, screamed about the assimilation of civilization. This caused mass panic before the government issued a formal message stating otherwise, and likely also related to the above incidents. "It has been a great tragedy for everyone involved, and a great concern for us, but we're expecting a full-scale military operation to investigate these abnormalities and restore public safety and order for all law-abiding members of society,” says the Minister of Public Safety. Despite these claims, it is currently debated whether a formalized military operation is necessary, but the situation should be solved, or at least better understood, very soon.
</div>
<br>
Goddamn fanatics, yeah, but ironically, they weren't so wrong. But that begs the question, doesn't it? Reflecting, the date was only on the eve of the crisis, so, obviously, no one would've had time to identify and collect all the bodies. The public met the event with indifference the moment the sky turned dark, and the winds turned gale, and after which was a moment of national grief. What I was standing amidst was the immediate aftermath of chaos, the destruction, littering, and bloodshed, yet no death, no bodies to count, no life either. It was peculiar, even surreal in a way.

My ponderings were unceremoniously interrupted by Trench's call to action. It looks like command wants environmental readings now that our lunch breaks are over. The other guys have already set up the drone and sent it flying and everything. Alright... I'll get to it.

