After I reported the environmental data back to command, Rough lifted the drill from the storage crate and booted it up. We had to drill 6 feet into a wall every few hundred meters we went. This was a mandatory practice to ensure that the tunnel's structural integrity would hold up for the rest of the journey, because hollow walls are a huge threat when you're deep down. There's even a saying: if you can hear your own footsteps echo or the noise of animals and waves outside, it may already be too late. But midway through drilling, it abruptly stopped. Grayish white fragments started flying out like shrapnel. Before we could even investigate this abnormality, an earsplitting screech inexplicably rang (whose origin was from some 2 kilometers tunneldownward, according to Coast) from far down, yet even from here we clutched our ears in distress. After the painstaking noise halted, we took a closer look at the hole we drilled. Inside were more of that white material, standing like a juxtaposition to the grey concrete on the exterior wall. Of what metal was it made of to suddenly halt a drill? Being the biologist I was, I immediately recognized that it wasn't metal. What it was made of would more accurately resemble the calcium, specifically the one found in human bones, reinforced in multiple layers. It was-

"Goddamnit, Whistler, did you hold the thing at the wrong angle again? You have to stop doing that!" exclaimed a heavily frustrated Coast

"No, I swear, to god, I was literally holding it at a 45-degree angle. Gosh, YOU need to stop jumping to conclusions, Coast. The walls aren't normal, nerd! Why do you think the tunnel screamed at us?"

"That's some of the most ridiculous bullshit I've heard from someone who's supposed to be smart!"

Before the quarrel could last longer, Trench stepped in to stop us and directly reported the anomaly to command. If Coast was originally quiet, now he was quiet and upset, only tiredly mentioning that the walls will likely be stable throughout the next 2 or 3 kilometers, not even bothering to show his work, but we still took his word for it anyway. Yet that would be the least of our worries about 5 minutes later. Wandering through the National Superbian Hospital, there was subtle shrieking and scraping against the jagged floor, akin to a mangled trench soldier crawling back to friendly lines, slowly bleeding out. At this time, we dismissed it as background noise and tried not to focus on it too much, as it would only cause a distraction to the task. Until my flashlight shone on a piece of police uniform buried under rubble, at least I thought so, and out it rose. It was a decaying skeleton, lacking facial features and a left arm. I braced for it to jump out and claw my face, but only through its movements did I realize that its entire lower torso was infused into the floor itself. There was a long, continuous dent throughout its entire body that could barely be called such. It opened its jaw in an attempt to make a noise. Yet no scream came. 

Its arm extended and crawled to us. Panicking, I stepped aside, knocking over a shelf and tripping over a bunch of jars, spilling expired medicine onto the already-moist floor. The thing's arm reached for my suit while I pulled away. Blood and adrenaline were flowing through my veins more than I could regulate. Each heartbeat felt physically painful. Desperate to get out of its grasp, I moved instinctively, slipping on the pills. Think about what you learned, Whistler! But I couldn't think, not when I could see its rotting skull and crooked arm caressing my body. Rough grabbed his Equalizer pistol and shot the thing with 2 trigger pulls, immobilizing its body while repeatedly stomping on its skull. I slid away from its corpse and heard another scream. Leaping even further back, I anticipated it attacking me. But no, and there was nothing to worry about, since its lifeless skeleton dissolved into the concrete below, leaving only the piece of ripped clothing behind.

It would've been any tunnel anomaly. Those were pretty common during missions, and we were taught how to deal with them to some degree. But any normal tunnel anomaly wouldn't be wearing a state-funded police uniform. And not especially with a silver ADF dogtag. With the name ''C. Hartman'' imprinted on it.

Duty calls, and we keep marching.

<big><big><center><span style="font-family: Plush-Trial">Harvest</span></center></big></big>

Approximately 2700 meters tunneldown Northwest. These wild ''Lithophyta obscura'' plants are renowned for surviving in the harsh environments of Level 335's lower tunnel system. These organisms aren't actually plants, so this original moniker I've introduced to you is quite inaccurate. Later scientific research revealed that these biological instances are actually a unique biological branch to adapt to the chemical reality of Ch-335, and more broadly, the environment of Level 335, and the justification of biologists for mistakenly identifying Obscura plants is because of the superficial similarities to terrestrial flora.

"Feelin' good, everyone?" I casually mention.

"Dizzy bit..." Coast said weakly. "I, ughh, probably shouldn't have... screamed so much, sorry. That's probably why I feel sick."

Rough hands me over the special shears I saved for the occasion. Just a word, when dealing with wild Obscura plants, you really have to be careful. The "stalk", if you could call it that, is a highly pressurized calcified siphon, meaning if I cut it too high, internal pressure rapidly goes down, the plant's dead, and it releases a bunch of Ch-335. You'd know from the subtle dusty beige in the air. And too low is also a death sentence. One wrong move and my visor, probably my face too, is melting in radiation. You have to find the really tiny two-to-four-millimeter neutral node in the plant's structure.

"Coast, keep your eyes on The Freezer. I get done with my gardening, and we get this in ASAP, or the entire thing dies."

Coast didn't reply; he just looked at me and gave a thumbs-up. Something felt strange about him. He was unusually disoriented, a lot more disoriented than the rest of us, and I wasn't saying I felt good after travelling such a distance either. Neither was the rest of the two. I continued collecting samples. After obtaining 10 unique instances, as my mission stated, I placed them in The Freezer and asked Coast to connect the preservation support systems. He was slightly drifting, as if he had just woken up from a very good dream, and Trench had to clap to get him to focus. Subsequently, regaining consciousness, he hooked up the wires and filled the ice-cold chamber with Ch-335 and slammed down on the lid at the last second before the samples could've gotten bad.

"Command, bio-samples successfully secured, retrieving now."

"Copy that, Regiment 6. Over."

The journey up was a bit more tiring than the journey down, but if there are two good things about going upwards, it's the feeling of finally seeing the sky again after 2 hours of grueling tunnel work and no more dreaded entity danger. At least we hoped so. Coast was complaining about a brutal migraine, so we were rushing a bit. But midway, probably around the 900-meter mark away from home, Coast abruptly dropped to the ground and vomited. We all panicked and asked him what was going on. Barely able to form words, he simply spurted out the word "sick". But that was when I noticed the microtear. A tiny, barely noticeable dent in his protective gear. Maybe the bone fragments shooting out pierced his gear, so all this time, Ch-335 gas has been accumulating within before we even knew it was too late. We were practically begging command to abandon the mission to get Coast up, but he insisted on staying because the equipment and samples were "unstable variables" and needed a professional like him to control them, and no amount of reasoning could convince him otherwise.

It was a race against time itself to get this sample up while getting Coast to safety. Rough went silent, being extremely focused on hauling the heavy machinery as quickly as possible while maintaining Coast's balance. Trench didn't look at his map anymore; he just ran through corridors and hand-signaled us to follow. By the time we reached to see the fog again, Coast was already knocked unconscious, and the stationed paramedics placed his still body on the gurney, put an oxygen mask over him, and rushed him to a nearby clinic. The last thing I heard while they escorted him was the wheels rolling, generating a high-pitched noise as they slid against the concrete floor, and only then did realized my hands were still shaking and my face was drenched in sweat.

<big><big><center><span style="font-family: Plush-Trial">Home</span></center></big></big>

Travelling all the way back from the facility after the suit decontamination process, I arrived at Bernhart Palace, my apartment building. Fancy name aside, it was anything but a place of royalty. Opening the metal door, my leather boots meet the sand beige welcome mat on the floor. The receptionist welcomed me in, and I asked for the key to my living space. Walking down the dimly lit hallway, dimly lit because the Ministry of Economics & Logistics implemented cost-cutting measures after the Crisis, I entered my room, and the smell of canned beef stew being reheated in the oven instantly hit my nose. The smell reminded me of the chemical preservatives back in The Freezer. Try not to think about it much, thinks I. Bethany was cleaning the dishes since she had eaten before me, and had already prepared a separate plate, which was sitting on the kitchen table.

"Hey, honey. You're late for dinner," she said. "I already ate a while ago."

"Long day. Uhm- coworker got into a nasty accident, and they made us stay longer back there to assess for any medical abnormalities or equipment failure. Sorry that I forgot to call you."

After polishing the last plate, she walked away from the sink and opened the oven door right when it was ready. I walked over to the sink, stared at it for a while, and turned on the faucet. Cold water met my sweaty hands, each one of my sensory nerves activated, as if I were holding an entire ice cube in the dawn of summer.

"Remember when we ate real food more often?" she said, pouring the canned beef stew into my plate. "On our third anniversary, we went to a local restaurant, and they had the best grilled salmon ever."

"I'm sorry, hun, we just can't afford that at the moment, y'know, mortgage and stuff-"

"Why do you need to apologize? I wasn't accusing you of anything. Well, I take back my words, why're ya spending so much time washing your hands?"

"Oh, right, uhmm, sorry... I just..."

"And your boots! You didn't bother with taking 'em off before you stepped in here? You get a bit distracted whenever you're home from work!"

Turning off the faucet and getting my boots off, which made me feel a lot lighter, I sat down on the kitchen chair near the plate of beef stew, grabbed a spoon, and started shoving spoonfuls into my mouth. It had a creamy, slightly mushy texture, with pieces of salty beef and small chunks of potato to chew on.

"It's a heavy question, but... do you still want a family someday?" asked Beth

"Oh, well... I mean, a family's great, I'd love to start a family, but we should really focus on paying our mortgages right now. Y'know, the recent disaster. I feel like it's best to focus on surviving here."

"Well, I know everything seems bad, honey, but... things are getting better. Anchoria's rebuilding the infrastructure, the economy, everything, and the new government is very focused on bettering the lives of us. Like, there are some great new systems in place that will surely help us out a lot. What I'm saying is that we can't just spend our lives waiting for the next disaster to strike."

I wanted to say something. Maybe reassuring her that everything will be okay. Maybe discussing whether her wantings were actually plausible or realistic enough. Maybe tell her about the dark tunnels and the gas and the zombie. Maybe just a simple reply. But my vocal cords felt too heavy then. With half of the energy I have left, I let out a sigh and replied:

"Right. I... I'm going to take a bath. Good night, sweetheart."

I stood up and carefully placed my plate on the sink. Just as my hand reached for the stair's handrails and my foot touched the first step, Bethany stopped me.

"You're avoidant." she said

"Oh, sweetie, I'm just tired... I swear, I'm too stressed to be partying or going out with other girls anyway."

"No, I know that. I just wished you were more open. I'm not asking for much. I'm not asking for you to immediately improve the situation right now or gift me something from your many voyages. But what happened to us planning the future together, so happy and sure that we'd do this? Do this together?"

"I understand, babe."

It was like the ocean's pressure just latched on to my back. As if I just got Chemical-335 poisoning. I open my cabinet and stare blankly at my clothes. Different colors, all neatly hanged, with one side being professional clothing and another for casual pairs. My arm reaches out and grabs a pair of casual clothing. Ch-335 poisoning. I walk to the bathroom and turn on the lights. Water melancholically drips from the showerhead and onto my hair and runs down my body. It's like the showers back in the decontamination facility! Ch-335 poisoning. A squirt of shampoo I add and I could feel its smooth bubble texture dancing on my hair. Ch-335 poisoning.

Walking out of the bathroom with my fresh pair of clothes on, I notice Bethany's graduation photo hung on the wall. That year she graduated from the University of National Sciences, just a year after me. She stood there, smiling widely in her sleek, black graduation gown, her eyes shining, as if she already had her life thought out. As if the universe was perfectly orderly, perfectly deterministic, perfectly predictable, perfect clarity, perfect... perfection...

Oh, it's 11 o'clock already! I'm exhausted, I'm going to sleep now.

<big><big><center><span style="font-family: Plush-Trial">Second Descent</span></center></big></big>

The hospital is sterile and clean, much more well-kept than the dilapidated Superbian Hospital down there. What room was he in again? 1335. The fluorescent lights hummed a song I wouldn't bother to decipher, but at least they were humming. I walked through the corridors and climbed down the stairs. There it was. <s>Chemic</s> ICU Room 1335. Trench was already inside, sitting on one of the empty beds opposite Coast's hospital bed, quietly contemplating, not shouting orders or talking to higher-ups.

It was surreal seeing Coast sleeping. It was surreal to think that it was surreal seeing Coast sleeping. He's usually quiet, not still. It was insane to think that a few microscopic molecules of gas managed to travel through such a miniscule crevice. And it was insane to think that he forgot to account for such a variable. But here I was, standing over his motionless body, kept alive by wires hooked to machines, keeping his pulse running in slow, quiet rhythms. Like acoustic guitar while sightseeing in the fog, except the only sight I'm seeing is this empty, soulless place of disease and the fog is metaphorically there. One single snap, one electrical outage, one tube malfunction and he's immediately gone. It pains me to see the human body in such a pitiful, fragile condition, being kept alive by a single point of failure.

"He'll wake up soon," said Trench. "It wasn't our fault man, we followed everything perfectly, it's okay."

"See, that's the problem, it was perfect, I-" but I stopped myself dead in my tracks. Stop looking at the physical body, Whistler. Look at Coast. Look at how you used to respect his intellect and no-nonsense mentality. He was an interesting individual. Unapproachable, but interesting, and knowledgeable. "Yeah, it wasn't our fault. I hope he recovers soon". Trench nods in etiquette, a respectful, comradely nod he learned from the countless formal meetings and military memorials he's gone too.

"Rough already went here a while ago. He was devastated when he called me to come over," said Trench. "Coast left us a small note next to his bed before he passed out. It's an instructional manual on how to operate the Preservation & Containment Crate. Might be important. I've already read it."

