"They don't have any substitute personnel available on board as of now, but they need the samples ASAP, so they're sending us down there anyways, just without Coast," said Trench. "Don't worry though, just remember basic equipment protocol training and whatever Coast wrote and we should make it out alive."

I clutched the note in my palm, tucked it in my pocket, and followed Trench out of the hospital.

The next week, the authorities sent us down there again, this time to retrieve Walking Jellyfish samples, except said samples can only be retrieved outside, 3000 meters down on the ocean floor. We'll be remote-controlling the Acheron-4, a submersible designed to withstand immense pressure, meant for sample retrieval and deep-sea exploration with its various built-in, remote-controlled gadgets. If that's the case, why did they send us down here again? Why not let the submarine do the entire thing? Well, we'll have to retrieve the sample early through a launch tube some 2500 meters down and snatch the sample before the 40-minute battery life runs out and the thing becomes lost government property. It can go where we can't, yet it can't come back by itself. They'll send another team down to retrieve the submersible itself after.

Superbia, my old friend. We crossed it again during this second descent, and the view of everything felt weirdly nostalgic, more nostalgic than the first time I went here on my first expedition. The only difference was that the hole we drilled last mission was gone. Nobody would've had the time to go down and patch the hole, so where was it? Besides that, there was everything I remembered was still here: the dilapidated, decaying infrastructure, the putrid air smell, the weird symbols. It was like the lingering ghost of the town had welcomed me again.

"I guess the insane people weren't entirely inaccurate about the fish-folk biology, it's objectively better for surviving in these types of rough environments, right?" I casually remark

"What the hell are you talking about, Whistler?" replies Rough

"Ermm... It's nothing. Yeah."

I didn't understand why I said that. Was I looking for something to say? Maybe it was the pressure, or the memory of Coast, or maybe I was just reciting nerd biology facts. Nobody would've understood my reference anyway. My monitor lit up and started sending back grainy, low-resolution images of the ocean in front of it, along with other technical jargon.

