The outside waters were dark and gloomy. We couldn't see anything beyond 60 meters, even with the Acheron's exploration-grade flashlight, and the monochromatic noise made seeing anything a lot more difficult. Sonar-based trackers told us more than the camera would ever, and they were detecting movement buried under the ocean floor, where the Walking Jellyfish resided. Just a few feet from the seabed, the Acheron-4 waited patiently for signs of movement on the floor. After a few seconds, one unlucky instance dug up, pulling the sand down, and started skittering away, likely in search of food. I told Rough to aim for one of its many appendages, since most of their nervous system resides there. Firing the harpoon from an upper angle, it landed squarely on one of the creature's legs, and it rolled up into an unconscious state, which we then subsequently transported into the Acheron's sample capsule.

Having taken one sample, we were going to transport it back to the launch tube and work on getting 4 more before the battery ran out. Yet despite trying my hardest to control the thing, it could only very slowly rise up to the surface at a mere 2-3 kilometers per hour. Walking Jellyfish aren't even heavy; they barely weigh anything. 14 minutes already, and it has barely scratched 400 meters. We were panicking because the battery was slowly dying, and we weren't making any progress. But the submersible would be the least of our worries at that moment as Rough noticed a weird glow in the corner of the hallway. It was an incorporeal, floating, malicious grin with no face, just two eyes and one large, glowing smile revealing its disgusting teeth. A smiler. We thought we were dead, and we turned on our flashlights to try and stop it, yet that didn't stop it from advancing towards us. But when it was, it was only a few feet close to us, it suddenly stopped. And oddly enough, it ran, or more accurately, floated away. Not out of mercy, no. In fear. But why? Was it our flashlights?

It was difficult to focus on the mission after that, but after a few seconds of relief, I looked at my monitor again, and still cautiously examined the hallway behind us. Rough kept his eyes on the door, with his Equalizer pointed at it and his index finger clutching the trigger.

