<big><big><center><span style="font-family: Plush-Trial">Lost</span></center></big></big>

Regaining consciousness, I found myself sitting on a chair in a sterile room. My ears were still ringing and my vision still blurry. The light above my head flickered. Was I still in the firefight? In front of me was a mahogany table, and a small wooden door completely sealed off the room from the outside. An officer in a light green MEG uniform sat on the opposite side of the table and questioned where I came from. Whatever this place was, it was definitely not Anchoria. I couldn’t immediately tell what level I was in from this singular room, either. But apparently I noclipped right in their frontyard, and since I had uniform that suggested I was affiliated with a group, they took me in for interrogation. It was a long, winding conversation. Some sentences long and some short, but undeniably the entire time I was there felt long and anxious. Frankly, I would’ve been more comfortable in my missions than this. An entire hour later, I finally got out of the room. Fresh air would’ve been a misnomer, but breathing felt way more comfortable when I was outside. And outside was a group of about 100 people. They were doing all sorts of activities —work, talking, laughing. But all I saw were 100 fragile, unsustainable biological machines. 100 people trying to survive in something they weren’t ever meant to survive in. They survived on scraps and whatever they could salvage, and yet still go around helping lost wanderers to safe spaces. It was pitiful, even a bit pathetic. I couldn’t even feel anger or frustrating, just a lingering sense of pity and disappointment for their inevitable collapse, and for the fact that they were so happily ignorant. And they probably didn’t respect me as anyone anyway, so why should I care about them? Why should I care about their useless, pitiful, inevitable fate existence? I never replied back to Bethany’s note before I went on that mission.

And standing here I was, reduced to a nameless nobody. I didn’t feel the need to be loyal to the MEG, definitely not, they were disgusting and incompetent. I don’t want to work with them, and I already told the officer that back in that room. I still got assigned research duty anyway. God, fuck them. I could fucking shoot him in the head right now. But my Rice Automatic wasn’t here anymore. But I tried suppressing that urge and just walk to my designated living space and take a nap. One of the MEG bumpkins, wearing a torn-up shirt, some old leather boots and a brown survival backpack, tried starting a conversation with me, but I just pushed him away. Maybe I’ll sleep and then I wake up and realize this entire thing was a dream. But I found great difficulty sleeping. Bethany. Trench. Will they remember me? Will Anchoria remember who I was? Will I remember what Anchoria was? I twist and twirl around in my wet mattress. I can’t process this. Not that I can’t. I just can’t. I’m not sure what biological process it was but I couldn’t care. I don’t want to care. I just wanted to sleep. But trying to not care is just making me care more. And trying to not care made it harder to sleep.

My doorbell rang. I still didn’t want to get out of bed yet, so I just sat there. There were no more doorbells so I just sat contemplating for 15 minutes before finally opening the door. There was but a can of spam and a note.

